# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alternating-current
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In the physics of electromagnetism, the **Abraham–Lorentz force** (also known as the **Lorentz–Abraham force**) is the reaction force on an accelerating charged particle caused by the particle emitting electromagnetic radiation by self-interaction.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] It is also called the **radiation reaction force**, the **radiation damping force**, or the **self-force**.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] It is named after the physicists Max Abraham and Hendrik Lorentz.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The formula, although predating the theory of special relativity, was initially calculated for non-relativistic velocity approximations.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] It was extended to arbitrary velocities by Max Abraham and was shown to be physically consistent by George Adolphus Schott.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The non-relativistic form is called **Lorentz self-force** while the relativistic version is called the **Lorentz–Dirac force** or collectively known as **Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac force**.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The equations are in the domain of classical physics, not quantum physics, and therefore may not be valid at distances of roughly the Compton wavelength or below.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] There are, however, two analogs of the formula that are both fully quantum and relativistic: one is called the "Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac–Langevin equation", the other is the self-force on a moving mirror.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The force is proportional to the square of the object's charge, multiplied by the jerk that it is experiencing.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] (Jerk is the rate of change of acceleration.) The force points in the direction of the jerk.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] For example, in a cyclotron, where the jerk points opposite to the velocity, the radiation reaction is directed opposite to the velocity of the particle, providing a braking action.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz force is the source of the radiation resistance of a radio antenna radiating radio waves.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] There are pathological solutions of the Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac equation in which a particle accelerates *in advance* of the application of a force, so-called *pre-acceleration* solutions.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Since this would represent an effect occurring before its cause (retrocausality), some theories have speculated that the equation allows signals to travel backward in time, thus challenging the physical principle of causality.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] One resolution of this problem was discussed by Arthur D.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Yaghjian and was further discussed by Fritz Rohrlich and Rodrigo Medina.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Furthermore, some authors argue that a radiation reaction force is unnecessary, introducing a corresponding stress-energy tensor that naturally conserves energy and momentum in Minkowski space and other suitable spacetimes.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Physically, an accelerating charge emits radiation (according to the Larmor formula), which carries momentum away from the charge.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Since momentum is conserved, the charge is pushed in the direction opposite the direction of the emitted radiation.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In fact the formula above for radiation force can be *derived* from the Larmor formula, as shown below.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Where $\gamma$ is the Lorentz factor associated with v , the velocity of particle.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The formula is consistent with special relativity and reduces to Lorentz's self-force expression for low velocity limit.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The first calculation of electromagnetic radiation energy due to current was given by George Francis FitzGerald in 1883, in which radiation resistance appears.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] However, dipole antenna experiments by Heinrich Hertz made a bigger impact and gathered commentary by Poincaré on the *amortissement* or damping of the oscillator due to the emission of radiation.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Qualitative discussions surrounding damping effects of radiation emitted by accelerating charges was sparked by Henri Poincaré in 1891.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In 1892, Hendrik Lorentz derived the self-interaction force of charges for low velocities but did not relate it to radiation losses.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Suggestion of a relationship between radiation energy loss and self-force was first made by Max Planck.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Planck's concept of the damping force, which did not assume any particular shape for elementary charged particles, was applied by Max Abraham to find the radiation resistance of an antenna in 1898, which remains the most practical application of the phenomenon.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In the early 1900s, Abraham formulated a generalization of the Lorentz self-force to arbitrary velocities, the physical consistency of which was later shown by George Adolphus Schott.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Schott was able to derive the Abraham equation and attributed "acceleration energy" to be the source of energy of the electromagnetic radiation.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Originally submitted as an essay for the 1908 Adams Prize, he won the competition and had the essay published as a book in 1912.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The relationship between self-force and radiation reaction became well-established at this point.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Wolfgang Pauli first obtained the covariant form of the radiation reaction and in 1938, Paul Dirac found that the equation of motion of charged particles, without assuming the shape of the particle, contained Abraham's formula within reasonable approximations.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The equations derived by Dirac are considered exact within the limits of classical theory.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The reverse situation, problems in which the fields are specified and the motion of particles are calculated.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In some fields of physics, such as plasma physics and the calculation of transport coefficients (conductivity, diffusivity, *etc.*), the fields generated by the sources and the motion of the sources are solved self-consistently.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In such cases, however, the motion of a selected source is calculated in response to fields generated by all other sources.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Rarely is the motion of a particle (source) due to the fields generated by that same particle calculated.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Inclusion of self-fields leads to problems in physics such as renormalization, some of which are still unsolved, that relate to the very nature of matter and energy.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz force is the result of the most fundamental calculation of the effect of self-generated fields.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] It arises from the observation that accelerating charges emit radiation.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz force is the average force that an accelerating charged particle feels in the recoil from the emission of radiation.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The introduction of quantum effects leads one to quantum electrodynamics.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The self-fields in quantum electrodynamics generate a finite number of infinities in the calculations that can be removed by the process of renormalization.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] This has led to a theory that is able to make the most accurate predictions that humans have made to date.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] (See precision tests of QED.) The renormalization process fails, however, when applied to the gravitational force.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The infinities in that case are infinite in number, which causes the failure of renormalization.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Therefore, general relativity has an unsolved self-field problem.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] String theory and loop quantum gravity are current attempts to resolve this problem, formally called the problem of radiation reaction or the problem of self-force.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The above expression can be integrated by parts.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] A generalized equation for arbitrary velocities was formulated by Max Abraham, which is found to be consistent with special relativity.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] An alternative derivation, making use of theory of relativity which was well established at that time, was found by Dirac without any assumption of the shape of the charged particle.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Below is an illustration of how a classical analysis can lead to surprising results.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The classical theory can be seen to challenge standard pictures of causality, thus signaling either a breakdown or a need for extension of the theory.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In this case the extension is to quantum mechanics and its relativistic counterpart quantum field theory.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] See the quote from Rohrlich in the introduction concerning "the importance of obeying the validity limits of a physical theory".
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The integral extends from the present to infinitely far in the future.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Thus future values of the force affect the acceleration of the particle in the present.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The future values are weighted by the factor $\exp \left(-{t'-t \over t_{0}}\right)$ which falls off rapidly for times greater than $t_{0}$ in the future.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Therefore, signals from an interval approximately $t_{0}$ into the future affect the acceleration in the present.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] For an electron, this time is approximately $10^{-24}$ sec, which is the time it takes for a light wave to travel across the "size" of an electron, the classical electron radius.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] One way to define this "size" is as follows: it is (up to some constant factor) the distance r such that two electrons placed at rest at a distance r apart and allowed to fly apart, would have sufficient energy to reach half the speed of light.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In other words, it forms the length (or time, or energy) scale where something as light as an electron would be fully relativistic.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] It is worth noting that this expression does not involve the Planck constant at all, so although it indicates something is wrong at this length scale, it does not directly relate to quantum uncertainty, or to the frequency–energy relation of a photon.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Although it is common in quantum mechanics to treat $\hbar \to 0$ as a "classical limit", some speculate that even the classical theory needs renormalization, no matter how the Planck constant would be fixed.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] To find the relativistic generalization, Dirac renormalized the mass in the equation of motion with the Abraham–Lorentz force in 1938.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] This renormalized equation of motion is called the Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac equation of motion.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Similar to the non-relativistic case, there are pathological solutions using the Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac equation that anticipate a change in the external force and according to which the particle accelerates *in advance* of the application of a force, so-called *preacceleration* solutions.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] One resolution of this problem was discussed by Yaghjian, and is further discussed by Rohrlich and Medina.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Runaway solutions are solutions to ALD equations that suggest the force on objects will increase exponentially over time.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The ALD equations are known to be zero for constant acceleration or hyperbolic motion in Minkowski spacetime diagram.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The subject of whether in such condition electromagnetic radiation exists was matter of debate until Fritz Rohrlich resolved the problem by showing that hyperbolically moving charges do emit radiation.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Subsequently, the issue is discussed in context of energy conservation and equivalence principle which is classically resolved by considering "acceleration energy" or Schott energy.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] However the antidamping mechanism resulting from the Abraham–Lorentz force can be compensated by other nonlinear terms, which are frequently disregarded in the expansions of the retarded Liénard–Wiechert potential.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac force leads to some pathological solutions.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Here $u^{i}=(\gamma ,\gamma \mathbf {v} /c)$ is the four-velocity of the particle, $\gamma =1/{\sqrt {1-v^{2}/c^{2}}}$ is the Lorentz factor and $\mathbf {v}$ is the three-dimensional velocity vector.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] where $D/Dt=\partial /\partial t+\mathbf {v} \cdot \nabla$ is the total derivative.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] While the Abraham–Lorentz force is largely neglected for many experimental considerations, it gains importance for plasmonic excitations in larger nanoparticles due to large local field enhancements.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Radiation damping acts as a limiting factor for the plasmonic excitations in surface-enhanced Raman scattering.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The damping force was shown to broaden surface plasmon resonances in gold nanoparticles, nanorods and clusters.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The effects of radiation damping on nuclear magnetic resonance were also observed by Nicolaas Bloembergen and Robert Pound, who reported its dominance over spin–spin and spin–lattice relaxation mechanisms for certain cases.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz force has been observed in the semiclassical regime in experiments which involve the scattering of a relativistic beam of electrons with a high intensity laser.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In the experiments, a supersonic jet of helium gas is intercepted by a high-intensity (1018–1020 W/cm2) laser.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The laser ionizes the helium gas and accelerates the electrons via what is known as the "laser-wakefield" effect.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] A second high-intensity laser beam is then propagated counter to this accelerated electron beam.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In a small number of cases, inverse-Compton scattering occurs between the photons and the electron beam, and the spectra of the scattered electrons and photons are measured.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The photon spectra are then compared with spectra calculated from Monte Carlo simulations that use either the QED or classical LL equations of motion.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The effects of radiation reaction are often considered within the framework of single-particle dynamics.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] However, interesting phenomena arise when a collection of charged particles is subjected to strong electromagnetic fields, such as in a plasma.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In such scenarios, the collective behavior of the plasma can significantly modify its properties due to radiation reaction effects.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Theoretical studies have shown that in environments with strong magnetic fields, like those found around pulsars and magnetars, radiation reaction cooling can alter the collective dynamics of the plasma.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] This modification can lead to instabilities within the plasma.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Specifically, in the high magnetic fields typical of these astrophysical objects, the momentum distribution of particles is bunched and becomes anisotropic due to radiation reaction forces, potentially driving plasma instabilities and affecting overall plasma behavior.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Among these instabilities, the firehose instability can arise due to the anisotropic pressure, and electron cyclotron maser due to population inversion in the rings.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] An alternate mechanism for radiation reaction on a point charge accelerated by an external force, is that the charge's increase in energy is diminished by the energy carried away by electromagnetic radiation.
[src:alternating-current/abraham-lorentz-force] This reduces the particle's acceleration without an additional force, and the paradoxes it causes are not there.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] An **AC motor** is an electric motor driven by an alternating current (AC).
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The AC motor commonly consists of two basic parts, an outside stator having coils supplied with alternating current to produce a rotating magnetic field, and an inside rotor attached to the output shaft producing a second rotating magnetic field.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The rotor magnetic field may be produced by permanent magnets, reluctance saliency, or DC or AC electrical windings.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Less common, AC linear motors operate on similar principles as rotating motors but have their stationary and moving parts arranged in a straight line configuration, producing linear motion instead of rotation.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The two main types of AC motors are induction motors and synchronous motors.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The induction motor (or asynchronous motor) always relies on a small difference in speed between the stator rotating magnetic field and the rotor shaft speed called slip to induce rotor current in the rotor AC winding.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] As a result, the induction motor cannot produce torque near synchronous speed where induction (or slip) is irrelevant or ceases to exist.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In contrast, the synchronous motor does not rely on slip-induction for operation and uses either permanent magnets, salient poles (having projecting magnetic poles), or an independently excited rotor winding.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The synchronous motor produces its rated torque at exactly synchronous speed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The brushless wound-rotor doubly fed synchronous motor system has an independently excited rotor winding that does not rely on the principles of slip-induction of current.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The brushless wound-rotor doubly fed motor is a synchronous motor that can function exactly at the supply frequency or sub to super multiple of the supply frequency.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Other types of motors include eddy current motors, and AC and DC mechanically commutated machines in which speed is dependent on voltage and winding connection.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Alternating current technology was rooted in Michael Faraday's and Joseph Henry's 1830–31 discovery that a changing magnetic field can induce an electric current in a circuit.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Faraday is usually given credit for this discovery since he published his findings first.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In 1832, French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii generated a crude form of alternating current when he designed and built the first alternator.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] It consisted of a revolving horseshoe magnet passing over two wound-wire coils.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Because of AC's advantages in long-distance high voltage transmission, there were many inventors in the United States and Europe during the late 19th century trying to develop workable AC motors.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The first person to conceive of a rotating magnetic field was Walter Baily, who gave a workable demonstration of his battery-operated polyphase motor aided by a commutator on 28 June 1879, to the Physical Society of London.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Describing an apparatus nearly identical to Baily's, French electrical engineer Marcel Deprez published a paper in 1880 that identified the rotating magnetic field principle and that of a two-phase AC system of currents to produce it.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Never practically demonstrated, the design was flawed, as one of the two currents was “furnished by the machine itself.” In 1886, English-born American engineer Elihu Thomson built an AC motor by expanding upon the induction-repulsion principle and his wattmeter.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In 1887, American inventor Charles Schenk Bradley was the first to patent a two-phase AC power transmission with four wires.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] "Commutatorless" alternating current induction motors seem to have been independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In 1888, Ferraris published his research to the Royal Academy of Sciences in Turin, where he detailed the foundations of motor operation; Tesla, in the same year, was granted a United States patent for his own motor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Working from Ferraris's experiments, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky introduced the first three-phase induction motor in 1890, a much more capable design that became the prototype used in Europe and the U.S.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] He also invented the first three-phase generator and transformer and combined them into the first complete AC three-phase system in 1891.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The three-phase motor design was also worked on by the Swiss engineer Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown, and other three-phase AC systems were developed by German technician Friedrich August Haselwander and Swedish engineer Jonas Wenström.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] If the rotor of a squirrel cage motor were to run at the true synchronous speed, the flux in the rotor at any given place on the rotor would not change, and no current would be created in the squirrel cage.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] For this reason, ordinary squirrel-cage motors run at some tens of revolutions per minute (RPM) slower than synchronous speed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Because the rotating field (or equivalent pulsating field) effectively rotates faster than the rotor, it could be said to *slip* past the surface of the rotor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The difference between synchronous speed and actual speed is called **slip**, and loading the motor increases the amount of slip as the motor slows down slightly.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Even with no load, internal mechanical losses prevent the slip from being zero.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The constant 120 results from combining the conversions of 60 seconds per minute and that each phase requires 2 poles.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Actual RPM for an induction motor will be less than this calculated synchronous speed by an amount known as *slip*, that increases with the torque produced.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] With no load, the speed will be very close to synchronous.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] When loaded, standard motors have between 2–3% slip, special motors may have up to 7% slip, and a class of motors known as *torque motors* are rated to operate at 100% slip (i.e., 0 rpm, full stall).
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] As an example, a typical four-pole motor running on 60 Hz might have a nameplate rating of 1725 rpm at full load, while its calculated speed is 1800 rpm.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The speed in this type of motor has traditionally been altered by having additional sets of coils or poles in the motor that can be switched on and off to change the speed of magnetic field rotation.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] However, developments in power electronics mean that the frequency of the power supply can also now be varied to provide a smoother control of the motor speed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This kind of rotor is the basic hardware for induction regulators, which is an exception of the use of rotating magnetic field as pure electrical (not electromechanical) application.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Most common AC motors use the squirrel-cage rotor, which will be found in virtually all domestic and light industrial alternating current motors.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The squirrel-cage refers to the rotating exercise cage for pet animals.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The motor takes its name from the shape of its rotor "windings"- a ring at either end of the rotor, with bars connecting the rings running the length of the rotor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] It is typically cast aluminum or copper poured between the iron laminates of the rotor, and usually only the end rings will be visible.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The vast majority of the rotor currents will flow through the bars rather than the higher-resistance and usually varnished laminates.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Very low voltages at very high currents are typical in the bars and end rings; high efficiency motors will often use cast copper to reduce the resistance in the rotor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In operation, the squirrel-cage motor may be viewed as a transformer with a rotating secondary.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] When the rotor is not rotating in sync with the magnetic field, large rotor currents are induced; the large rotor currents magnetize the rotor and interact with the stator's magnetic fields to bring the rotor almost into synchronization with the stator's field.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] An unloaded squirrel-cage motor at rated no-load speed will consume electrical power only to maintain rotor speed against friction and resistance losses.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] As the mechanical load increases, so will the electrical load – the electrical load is inherently related to the mechanical load.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This is similar to a transformer, where the primary's electrical load is related to the secondary's electrical load.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This is why a squirrel-cage blower motor may cause household lights to dim upon starting, but does not dim the lights on startup when its fan belt (and therefore mechanical load) is removed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Furthermore, a stalled squirrel-cage motor (overloaded or with a jammed shaft) will consume current limited only by circuit resistance as it attempts to start.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Unless something else limits the current (or cuts it off completely) overheating and destruction of the winding insulation is the likely outcome.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Many washing machines, dishwashers, larger standalone fans, compressors, etc. use some variant of a squirrel-cage motor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] An alternate design, called the wound rotor motor, is used when variable speed is required.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In this case, the rotor has the same number of poles as the stator and the windings are made of wire, connected to slip rings on the shaft.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Carbon brushes connect the slip rings to a controller such as a variable resistor that allows changing the motor's slip rate.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In certain high-power variable-speed wound rotor drives, the slip-frequency energy is captured, rectified, and returned to the power supply through an inverter.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] With bidirectionally controlled power, the wound rotor becomes an active participant in the energy conversion process, with the wound rotor doubly fed configuration showing twice the power density.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Compared to squirrel cage rotors, wound rotor motors are expensive and require maintenance of the slip rings and brushes, but they were the standard form for variable speed control before the advent of compact power electronic devices.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Transistorized inverters with variable-frequency drive can now be used for speed control, and wound rotor motors are becoming less common.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Several methods of starting a polyphase motor are used.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Where a large inrush current and high starting torque can be permitted, the motor can be started across the line, by applying full line voltage to the terminals (direct-on-line, DOL).
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Where it is necessary to limit the starting inrush current (where the motor is large compared with the short-circuit capacity of the supply), the motor is started at reduced voltage using either series inductors, an autotransformer, thyristors, or other devices.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] A technique sometimes used is star-delta (YΔ) starting, where the motor coils are initially connected in star configuration for acceleration of the load, then switched to delta configuration when the load is up to speed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This technique is more common in Europe than in North America.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Transistorized drives can directly vary the applied voltage as required by the starting characteristics of the motor and load.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This type of motor is becoming more common in traction applications such as locomotives, where it is known as the asynchronous traction motor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] 2. a control-voltage (AC) winding in quadrature (i.e., 90 degrees phase shifted) with the main winding so as to produce a rotating magnetic field.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Reversing phase makes the motor reverse.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] An AC servo amplifier, a linear power amplifier, feeds the control winding.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The electrical resistance of the rotor is made high intentionally so that the speed–torque curve is fairly linear.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Two-phase servo motors are inherently high-speed, low-torque devices, heavily geared down to drive the load.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Single-phase motors do not have a unique rotating magnetic field like multi-phase motors.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The field alternates (reverses polarity) between pole pairs and can be viewed as two fields rotating in opposite directions.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] They require a secondary magnetic field that causes the rotor to move in a specific direction.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] After starting, the alternating stator field is in relative rotation with the rotor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] A common single-phase motor is the shaded-pole motor and is used in devices requiring low starting torque, such as electric fans, small pumps, or small household appliances.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In this motor, small single-turn copper "shading coils" create the moving magnetic field.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Part of each pole is encircled by a copper coil or strap; the induced current in the strap opposes the change of flux through the coil.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This causes a time lag in the flux passing through the shading coil, so that the maximum field intensity moves higher across the pole face on each cycle.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This produces a low level rotating magnetic field which is large enough to turn both the rotor and its attached load.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] As the rotor picks up speed the torque builds up to its full level as the principal magnetic field is rotating relative to the rotating rotor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] A **reversible shaded-pole motor** was made by Barber-Colman several decades ago.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] It had a single field coil, and two principal poles, each split halfway to create two pairs of poles.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Each of these four "half-poles" carried a coil, and the coils of diagonally opposite half-poles were connected to a pair of terminals.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] One terminal of each pair was common, so only three terminals were needed in all.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The motor would not start with the terminals open; connecting the common to one made the motor run one way, and connecting the common to the other made it run the other way.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] These motors were used in industrial and scientific devices.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] An unusual, **adjustable-speed**, low-torque shaded-pole motor could be found in traffic-light and advertising-lighting controllers.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The pole faces were parallel and relatively close to each other, with the disc centered between them, something like the disc in a watthour electricity meter.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Each pole face was split, and had a shading coil on one part; the shading coils were on the parts that faced each other.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Applying AC to the coil created a field that progressed in the gap between the poles.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The plane of the stator core was approximately tangential to an imaginary circle on the disc, so the travelling magnetic field dragged the disc and made it rotate.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The stator was mounted on a pivot so it could be positioned for the desired speed and then clamped in position.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Placing the poles nearer to the center of the disc made it run faster, and toward the edge, slower.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Another common single-phase AC motor is the *split-phase induction motor*, commonly used in major appliances such as air conditioners and clothes dryers.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Compared to the shaded pole motor, these motors provide much greater starting torque.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] A split-phase motor has a secondary startup winding that is 90 electrical degrees to the main winding, always centered directly between the poles of the main winding, and connected to the main winding by a set of electrical contacts.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The coils of this winding are wound with fewer turns of smaller wire than the main winding, so it has a lower inductance and higher resistance.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The position of the winding creates a small phase shift between the flux of the main winding and the flux of the starting winding, causing the rotor to rotate.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] When the speed of the motor is sufficient to overcome the inertia of the load, the contacts are opened automatically by a centrifugal switch or electric relay.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The direction of rotation is determined by the connection between the main winding and the start circuit.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In applications where the motor requires a fixed rotation, one end of the start circuit is permanently connected to the main winding, with the contacts making the connection at the other end.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] A capacitor start motor is a split-phase induction motor with a starting motor capacitor inserted in series with the startup winding, creating an LC circuit which produces a greater phase shift (and so, a much greater starting torque) than both split-phase and shaded pole motors.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This motor has a centrifugal switch which disconnects the capacitor once the motor has started.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This motor provides high starting torque.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This motor provides high starting torque and high efficiency.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] A resistance start motor is a split-phase induction motor with a starter inserted in series with the startup winding, creating reactance.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This added starter provides assistance in the starting and initial direction of rotation.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The start winding is made mainly of thin wire with fewer turns to make it high resistive and less inductive.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The main winding is made with thicker wire with larger number of turns which makes it less resistive and more inductive.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Another variation is the *permanent-split capacitor (or PSC) motor*.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Also known as a capacitor-run motor, this type of motor uses a non-polarized capacitor with a high voltage rating to generate an electrical phase shift between the run and start windings.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] PSC motors are the dominant type of split-phase motor in Europe and much of the world, but in North America, they are most frequently used in variable torque applications (like blowers, fans, and pumps) and other cases where variable speeds are desired.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] A capacitor with a relatively low capacitance, and relatively high voltage rating, is connected in series with the start winding and remains in the circuit during the entire run cycle.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Like other split-phase motors, the main winding is used with a smaller start winding, and rotation is changed by reversing the connection between the main winding and the start circuit, or by having polarity of main winding switched while start winding is always connected to a capacitor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] There are significant differences, however; the use of a speed sensitive centrifugal switch requires that other split-phase motors must operate at, or very close to, full speed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] PSC motors may operate within a wide range of speeds, much lower than the motor's electrical speed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Also, for applications like automatic door openers that require the motor to reverse rotation often, the use of a mechanism requires that a motor must slow to a near stop before contact with the start winding is re-established.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The 'permanent' connection to the capacitor in a PSC motor means that changing rotation is instantaneous.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Three-phase motors can be converted to PSC motors by making common two windings and connecting the third via a capacitor to act as a start winding.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] However, the power rating needs to be at least 50% larger than for a comparable single-phase motor due to an unused winding.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The synchronous motor can also be used as an alternator.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Contemporary synchronous motors are frequently driven by solid state variable-frequency drives.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This greatly eases the problem of starting the massive rotor of a large synchronous motor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Synchronous motors are occasionally used as traction motors; the TGV may be the best-known example of such use.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Huge numbers of three phase synchronous motors are now fitted to electric cars.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] They have a neodymium or other rare-earth permanent magnet.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] One use for this type of motor is its use in a power factor correction scheme.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] They are referred to as synchronous condensers.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This exploits a feature of the machine where it consumes power at a leading power factor when its rotor is over excited.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] It thus appears to the supply to be a capacitor, and could thus be used to correct the lagging power factor that is usually presented to the electric supply by inductive loads.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The excitation is adjusted until a near unity power factor is obtained (often automatically).
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Machines used for this purpose are easily identified as they have no shaft extensions.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Synchronous motors are valued in any case because their power factor is much better than that of induction motors, making them preferred for very high power applications.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Some of the largest AC motors are pumped-storage hydroelectricity generators that are operated as synchronous motors to pump water to a reservoir at a higher elevation for later use to generate electricity using the same machinery.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Six 500-megawatt generators are installed in the Bath County Pumped Storage Station in Virginia, USA.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] When pumping, each unit can produce 642,800 horsepower (479.3 megawatts).
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Small single-phase AC motors can also be designed with magnetized rotors (or several variations on that idea; see "Hysteresis synchronous motors" below).
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] If a conventional squirrel-cage rotor has flats ground on it to create salient poles and increase reluctance, it will start conventionally, but will run synchronously, although it can provide only a modest torque at synchronous speed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Because inertia makes it difficult to instantly accelerate the rotor from stopped to synchronous speed, these motors normally require some sort of special feature to get started.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Some include a squirrel-cage structure to bring the rotor close to synchronous speed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Various other designs use a small induction motor (which may share the same field coils and rotor as the synchronous motor) or a very light rotor with a one-way mechanism (to ensure that the rotor starts in the "forward" direction).
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In the latter instance, applying AC power creates chaotic (or seemingly chaotic) jumping movement back and forth; such a motor will always start, but lacking the anti-reversal mechanism, the direction it runs is unpredictable.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The Hammond organ tone generator used a non-self-starting synchronous motor (until comparatively recently), and had an auxiliary conventional shaded-pole starting motor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] A spring-loaded auxiliary manual starting switch connected power to this second motor for a few seconds.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] These motors are relatively costly, and are used where exact speed (assuming an exact-frequency AC source) and rotation with low flutter (high-frequency variation in speed) are essential.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Applications included tape recorder capstan drives (the motor shaft could be the capstan), and, before the advent of crystal control, motion picture cameras and recorders.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Their distinguishing feature is their rotor, which is a smooth cylinder of a magnetic alloy that stays magnetized, but can be demagnetized fairly easily as well as re-magnetized with poles in a new location.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Hysteresis refers to how the magnetic flux in the metal lags behind the external magnetizing force; for instance, to demagnetize such a material, one could apply a magnetizing field of opposite polarity to that which originally magnetized the material.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] These motors have a stator like those of capacitor-run squirrel-cage induction motors.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] On startup, when slip decreases sufficiently, the rotor becomes magnetized by the stator's field, and the poles stay in place.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The motor then runs at synchronous speed as if the rotor were a permanent magnet.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] When stopped and restarted, the poles are likely to form at different locations.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] For a given design, torque at synchronous speed is only relatively modest, and the motor can run at below synchronous speed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In simple words, it is lagging magnetic field behind magnetic flux.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] A universal motor is a design that can operate on either AC or DC power.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In universal motors the stator and rotor of a brushed DC motor are both wound and supplied from an external source, with the torque being a function of the rotor current times the stator current so reversing the current in both rotor and stator does not reverse the rotation.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Universal motors can run on AC as well as DC provided the frequency is not so high that the inductive reactance of the stator winding and eddy current losses become problems.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Nearly all universal motors are series-wound because their stators have relatively few turns, minimizing inductance.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Universal motors are compact, have high starting torque and can be varied in speed over a wide range with relatively simple controls such as rheostats and PWM choppers.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Compared with induction motors, universal motors do have some drawbacks inherent to their brushes and commutators: relatively high levels of electrical and acoustic noise, low reliability and more frequent required maintenance.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Universal motors are widely used in small home appliances and hand power tools.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Until the 1970s they dominated electric traction (electric, including diesel-electric railway and road vehicles); many traction power networks still use special low frequencies such as 16.7 and 25 Hz to overcome the aforementioned problems with losses and reactance.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Still widely used, universal traction motors have been increasingly displaced by polyphase AC induction and permanent magnet motors with variable-frequency drives made possible by modern power semiconductor devices.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Repulsion motors are wound-rotor single-phase AC motors that are a type of induction motor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In a repulsion motor, the armature brushes are shorted together rather than connected in series with the field, as is done with universal motors.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] By transformer action, the stator induces currents in the rotor, which create torque by repulsion instead of attraction as in other motors.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Several types of repulsion motors have been manufactured, but the *repulsion-start induction-run* (RS-IR) motor has been used most frequently.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The RS-IR motor has a centrifugal switch that shorts all segments of the commutator so that the motor operates as an induction motor once it is close to full speed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Some of these motors also lift the brushes out of contact with source voltage regulation.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Repulsion motors were developed before suitable motor starting capacitors were available, and few repulsion motors are sold as of 2005.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Where speed stability is important, some AC motors (such as some Papst motors) have the stator on the inside and the rotor on the outside to optimize inertia and cooling.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Exterior rotors are also common in ceiling fan motors.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] A conical rotor brake motor incorporates the brake as an integral part of the conical sliding rotor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] When the motor is at rest, a spring acts on the sliding rotor and forces the brake ring against the brake cap in the motor, holding the rotor stationary.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] When the motor is energized, its magnetic field generates both an axial and a radial component.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The axial component overcomes the spring force, releasing the brake; while the radial component causes the rotor to turn.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] There is no additional brake control required.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The high starting torque and low inertia of the conical rotor brake motor has proven to be ideal for the demands of high cycle dynamic drives in applications since the motor was invented, designed and introduced over 50 years ago.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This type of motor configuration was first introduced in the US in 1963.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Single-speed or two speed motors are designed for coupling to gear motor system gearboxes.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Conical rotor brake motors are also used to power micro speed drives.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Motors of this type can also be found on overhead cranes and hoists.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The micro speed unit combines two motors and an intermediate gear reducer.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] These are used for applications where extreme mechanical positioning accuracy and high cycling capability are needed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The micro speed unit combines a “main” conical rotor brake motor for rapid speed and a “micro” conical rotor brake motor for slow or positioning speed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The intermediate gearbox allows a range of ratios, and motors of different speeds can be combined to produce high ratios between high and low speed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Electronically commutated (EC) motors are electric motors powered by direct-current (DC) electricity and having electronic commutation systems, rather than mechanical commutators and brushes.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The current-to-torque and frequency-to-speed relationships of BLDC motors are linear.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] While the motor coils are powered by DC, power may be rectified from AC within the casing.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] These are two-phase induction motors with permanent magnets to retard the rotor so its speed is accurately proportional to the power passing through the meter.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The rotor is an aluminium-alloy disc, and currents induced into it react with the field from the stator.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] A split-phase watthour electricity meter has a stator with three coils facing the disc.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The magnetic circuit is completed by a C-shaped core of permeable iron.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The "voltage" coil above the disc is in parallel with the supply; its many turns have a high inductance/resistance ratio (Q) so its current and magnetic field are the time integral of the applied voltage, lagging it by 90 degrees.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This magnetic field passes down perpendicularly through the disc, inducing circular eddy currents in the plane of the disc centered on the field.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] These induced currents are proportional to the time derivative of the magnetic field, leading it by 90 degrees.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This puts the eddy currents in phase with the voltage applied to the voltage coil, just as the current induced in the secondary of a transformer with a resistive load is in phase with the voltage applied to its primary.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The eddy currents pass directly above the pole pieces of two "current" coils under the disc, each wound with a few turns of heavy-gauge wire whose inductive reactance is small compared to the load impedance.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] These coils connect the supply to the load, producing a magnetic field in phase with the load current.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] This field passes from the pole of one current coil up perpendicularly through the disc and back down through the disc to the pole of the other current coil, with a completed magnetic circuit back to the first current coil.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] As these fields cross the disc, they pass through the eddy currents induced in it by the voltage coil producing a Lorentz force on the disc mutually perpendicular to both.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Assuming power is flowing to the load, the flux from the left current coil crosses the disc upwards where the eddy current flows radially toward the center of the disc producing (by the right-hand rule) a torque driving the front of the disc to the right.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Similarly, the flux crosses down through the disc to the right current coil where the eddy current flows radially away from the disc center, again producing a torque driving the front of the disc to the right.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] When the AC polarity reverses, the eddy currents in the disc and the direction of the magnetic flux from the current coils both change, leaving the direction of the torque unchanged.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The torque is thus proportional to the instantaneous line voltage times the instantaneous load current, automatically correcting for power factor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The disc is braked by a permanent magnet so that speed is proportional to torque and the disc mechanically integrates real power.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The mechanical dial on the meter reads disc rotations and the total net energy delivered to the load.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In a split-phase watthour meter the voltage coil is connected between the two "hot" (line) terminals (240 V in North America) and two separate current coils are connected between the corresponding line and load terminals.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] No connection to the system neutral is needed to correctly handle combined line-to-neutral and line-to-line loads.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Line-to-line loads draw the same current through both current coils and spin the meter twice as fast as a line-to-neutral load drawing the same current through only a single current coil, correctly registering the power drawn by the line-to-line load as twice that of the line-to-neutral load.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Other variations of the same design are used for polyphase (e.g., three-phase) power.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Representative are low-torque synchronous motors with a multi-pole hollow cylindrical magnet (internal poles) surrounding the stator structure.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The stator has one coil, coaxial with the shaft.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] At each end of the coil are a pair of circular plates with rectangular teeth on their edges, formed so they are parallel with the shaft.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] One of the pair of discs distributes the coil's flux directly, while the other receives flux that has passed through a common shading coil.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] The poles are rather narrow, and between the poles leading from one end of the coil are an identical set leading from the other end.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] In all, this creates a repeating sequence of four poles, unshaded alternating with shaded, that creates a circumferential traveling field to which the rotor's magnetic poles rapidly synchronize.
[src:alternating-current/ac-motor] Some stepping motors have a similar structure.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] In an electric circuit, instantaneous power is the time rate of flow of energy past a given point of the circuit.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] In alternating current circuits, energy storage elements such as inductors and capacitors may result in periodic reversals of the direction of energy flow.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The portion of instantaneous power that, averaged over a complete cycle of the AC waveform, results in net transfer of energy in one direction is known as instantaneous active power, and its time average is known as **active power** or **real power**.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The portion of instantaneous power that results in no net transfer of energy but instead oscillates between the source and load in each cycle due to stored energy is known as instantaneous reactive power, and its amplitude is the absolute value of **reactive power**.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The **instantaneous power** is given by the product: $p(t)=v(t)i(t)=2{|V|}{|I|}\cos(\omega t)\cos(\omega t-\varphi ).$ If the load is purely resistive, the two quantities reverse their polarity at the same time.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Hence, the instantaneous power is always positive, such that the direction of energy flow does not reverse and always is toward the resistor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] In this case, only active power is transferred.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] If the load is purely *reactive*, then the voltage and current are 90 degrees out of phase.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] For two quarters of each cycle, the product of voltage and current is positive, but for the other two quarters, the product is negative, indicating that on average, exactly as much energy flows into the load as flows back out.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] There is no net energy flow over each half cycle.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] In this case, only reactive power flows: There is no net transfer of energy to the load; however, electrical power does flow along the wires and returns by flowing in reverse along the same wires.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The current required for this reactive power flow dissipates energy in the line resistance, even if the ideal load device consumes no energy itself.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Practical loads have resistance as well as inductance, or capacitance, so both active and reactive powers will flow to normal loads.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Apparent power is the product of the RMS values of voltage and current.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Apparent power is taken into account when designing and operating power systems, because although the current associated with reactive power does no work at the load, it still must be supplied by the power source.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Conductors, transformers and generators must be sized to carry the total current, not just the current that does useful work.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Insufficient reactive power can depress voltage levels on an electrical grid and, under certain operating conditions, collapse the network (a blackout).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Another consequence is that adding the apparent power for two loads will not accurately give the total power unless they have the same phase difference between current and voltage (the same power factor).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Conventionally, capacitors are treated as if they generate reactive power, and inductors are treated as if they consume it.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] If a capacitor and an inductor are placed in parallel, then the currents flowing through the capacitor and the inductor tend to cancel rather than add.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] This is the fundamental mechanism for controlling the power factor in electric power transmission; capacitors (or inductors) are inserted in a circuit to partially compensate for reactive power 'consumed' ('generated') by the load.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Purely capacitive circuits supply reactive power with the current waveform leading the voltage waveform by 90 degrees, while purely inductive circuits absorb reactive power with the current waveform lagging the voltage waveform by 90 degrees.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The result of this is that capacitive and inductive circuit elements tend to cancel each other out.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] These are all denoted in the adjacent diagram (called a power triangle).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] In the diagram, *P* is the active power, *Q* is the reactive power (in this case positive), *S* is the complex power and the length of *S* is the apparent power.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Reactive power does not do any work, so it is represented as the **imaginary axis** of the vector diagram.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Active power does do work, so it is the real axis.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The unit for power is the watt (symbol: W).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Apparent power is often expressed in volt-amperes (VA) since it is the product of RMS voltage and RMS current.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The unit for reactive power is var, which stands for volt-ampere reactive.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Since reactive power transfers no net energy to the load, it is sometimes called "wattless" power.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] It does, however, serve an important function in electrical grids and its lack has been cited as a significant factor in the Northeast blackout of 2003.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Understanding the relationship among these three quantities lies at the heart of understanding power engineering.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The mathematical relationship among them can be represented by vectors or expressed using complex numbers, *S* = *P* + *j Q* (where *j* is the imaginary unit).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] where V and I are the complex valued voltage and current, respectively, written in phasor form with the amplitude as RMS.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Also by convention, the complex conjugate of *I* is used, which is denoted $I^{*}$ (or ${\overline {I}}$ ), rather than *I* itself.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] This is done because otherwise using the product V I to define S would result in a quantity that depends on the reference angle chosen for V or I, but defining S as V I* results in a quantity that doesn't depend on the reference angle and allows to relate S to P and Q.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Other forms of complex power (units in volt-amps, VA) are derived from *Z*, the load impedance (units in ohms, Ω).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] where *X* denotes reactance (units in ohms, Ω) of the load.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] These are simplified diagrammatically by the power triangle.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The ratio of active power to apparent power in a circuit is called the power factor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] For two systems transmitting the same amount of active power, the system with the lower power factor will have higher circulating currents due to energy that returns to the source from energy storage in the load.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] These higher currents produce higher losses and reduce overall transmission efficiency.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] A lower power factor circuit will have a higher apparent power and higher losses for the same amount of active power.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The power factor is 1.0 when the voltage and current are in phase.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] It is zero when the current leads or lags the voltage by 90 degrees.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] When the voltage and current are 180 degrees out of phase, the power factor is negative one, and the load is feeding energy into the source (an example would be a home with solar cells on the roof that feed power into the power grid when the sun is shining).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Power factors are usually stated as "leading" or "lagging" to show the sign of the phase angle of current with respect to voltage.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Voltage is designated as the base to which current angle is compared, meaning that current is thought of as either "leading" or "lagging" voltage.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Where the waveforms are purely sinusoidal, the power factor is the cosine of the phase angle ( $\varphi$ ) between the current and voltage sinusoidal waveforms.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Equipment data sheets and nameplates will often abbreviate power factor as " $\cos \varphi$ " for this reason.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Example: The active power is 700 W and the phase angle between voltage and current is 45.6°.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] In a direct current circuit, the power flowing to the load is proportional to the product of the current through the load and the potential drop across the load.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The power that happens because of a capacitor or inductor is called reactive power.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] It happens because of the AC nature of elements like inductors and capacitors.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Energy flows in one direction from the source to the load.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] In AC power, the voltage and current both vary approximately sinusoidally.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] When there is inductance or capacitance in the circuit, the voltage and current waveforms do not line up perfectly.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The power flow has two components – one component flows from source to load and can perform work at the load; the other portion, known as "reactive power", is due to the delay between voltage and current, known as phase angle, and cannot do useful work at the load.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] It can be thought of as current that is arriving at the wrong time (too late or too early).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] To distinguish reactive power from active power, it is measured in units of "volt-amperes reactive", or var.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] These units can simplify to watts but are left as var to denote that they represent no actual work output.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Energy stored in capacitive or inductive elements of the network gives rise to reactive power flow.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Reactive power flow strongly influences the voltage levels across the network.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Voltage levels and reactive power flow must be carefully controlled to allow a power system to be operated within acceptable limits.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] A technique known as reactive compensation is used to reduce apparent power flow to a load by reducing reactive power supplied from transmission lines and providing it locally.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] For example, to compensate an inductive load, a shunt capacitor is installed close to the load itself.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] This allows all reactive power needed by the load to be supplied by the capacitor and not have to be transferred over the transmission lines.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] This practice saves energy because it reduces the amount of energy that is required to be produced by the utility to do the same amount of work.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Additionally, it allows for more efficient transmission line designs using smaller conductors or fewer bundled conductors and optimizing the design of transmission towers.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Stored energy in the magnetic or electric field of a load device, such as a motor or capacitor, causes an offset between the current and the voltage waveforms.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] A capacitor is a device that stores energy in the form of an electric field.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] As current is driven through the capacitor, charge build-up causes an opposing voltage to develop across the capacitor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] This voltage increases until some maximum dictated by the capacitor structure.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] In an AC network, the voltage across a capacitor is constantly changing.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The capacitor opposes this change, causing the current to lead the voltage in phase.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Capacitors are said to "source" reactive power, and thus to cause a leading power factor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Induction machines are some of the most common types of loads in the electric power system today.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] These machines use inductors, or large coils of wire to store energy in the form of a magnetic field.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] When a voltage is initially placed across the coil, the inductor strongly resists this change in a current and magnetic field, which causes a time delay for the current to reach its maximum value.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] This causes the current to lag behind the voltage in phase.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Inductors are said to "sink" reactive power, and thus to cause a lagging power factor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Induction generators can source or sink reactive power, and provide a measure of control to system operators over reactive power flow and thus voltage.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Because these devices have opposite effects on the phase angle between voltage and current, they can be used to "cancel out" each other's effects.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] This usually takes the form of capacitor banks being used to counteract the lagging power factor caused by induction motors.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Transmission connected generators are generally required to support reactive power flow.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] For example, on the United Kingdom transmission system, generators are required by the Grid Code Requirements to supply their rated power between the limits of 0.85 power factor lagging and 0.90 power factor leading at the designated terminals.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The "system gain" is an important source of reactive power in the above power balance equation, which is generated by the capacitative nature of the transmission network itself.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] By making decisive switching actions in the early morning before the demand increases, the system gain can be maximized early on, helping to secure the system for the whole day.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] To balance the equation some pre-fault reactive generator use will be required.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Other sources of reactive power that will also be used include shunt capacitors, shunt reactors, static VAR compensators and voltage control circuits.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] While active power and reactive power are well defined in any system, the definition of apparent power for unbalanced polyphase systems is considered to be one of the most controversial topics in power engineering.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Originally, apparent power arose merely as a figure of merit.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Major delineations of the concept are attributed to Stanley's *Phenomena of Retardation in the Induction Coil* (1888) and Steinmetz's *Theoretical Elements of Engineering* (1915).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] However, with the development of three-phase power distribution, it became clear that the definition of apparent power and the power factor could not be applied to unbalanced polyphase systems.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] In 1920, a "Special Joint Committee of the AIEE and the National Electric Light Association" met to resolve the issue.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] that is, the magnitude of total three-phase complex power.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The 1920 committee found no consensus and the topic continued to dominate discussions.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] In 1932, another committee formed and once again failed to resolve the question.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] The transcripts of their discussions are the lengthiest and most controversial ever published by the AIEE.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Further resolution of this debate did not come until the late 1990s.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] $V^{+}$ denotes the positive sequence voltage phasor, and $I^{+}$ denotes the positive sequence current phasor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] A perfect resistor stores no energy; so current and voltage are in phase.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Therefore, there is no reactive power and $P=S$ (using the passive sign convention).
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] For a perfect capacitor or inductor, there is no net power transfer; so all power is reactive.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] where *X* is the reactance of the capacitor or inductor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] where $v(t)$ and $i(t)$ are the time-varying voltage and current waveforms.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] This definition is useful because it applies to all waveforms, whether they are sinusoidal or not.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] This is particularly useful in power electronics, where non-sinusoidal waveforms are common.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] In general, engineers are interested in the active power averaged over a period of time, whether it is a low frequency line cycle or a high frequency power converter switching period.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] This method of calculating the average power gives the active power regardless of harmonic content of the waveform.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Since an RMS value can be calculated for any waveform, apparent power can be calculated from this.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] For active power it would at first appear that it would be necessary to calculate many product terms and average all of them.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] However, looking at one of these product terms in more detail produces a very interesting result.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] However, the time average of a function of the form cos(*ωt* + *k*) is zero provided that *ω* is nonzero.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Therefore, the only product terms that have a nonzero average are those where the frequency of voltage and current match.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] In other words, it is possible to calculate active (average) power by simply treating each frequency separately and adding up the answers.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Furthermore, if voltage of the mains supply is assumed to be a single frequency (which it usually is), this shows that harmonic currents are a bad thing.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] They will increase the RMS current (since there will be non-zero terms added) and therefore apparent power, but they will have no effect on the active power transferred.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Hence, harmonic currents will reduce the power factor.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Harmonic currents can be reduced by a filter placed at the input of the device.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] Typically this will consist of either just a capacitor (relying on parasitic resistance and inductance in the supply) or a capacitor-inductor network.
[src:alternating-current/ac-power] An active power factor correction circuit at the input would generally reduce the harmonic currents further and maintain the power factor closer to unity.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] In physics, **acceleration** is a measure of how fast and in what direction an object's speed and direction of motion are changing.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] It is defined as the rate of change of the velocity.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Like velocity, acceleration has a magnitude and a direction, making it a vector quantity.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] The SI unit for acceleration is metre per second squared (m⋅s−2, m/s2).
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] The **tangential acceleration** of an object is the component of the **acceleration** which is in the same direction as the motion (or tangential velocity) of the object.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] When the velocity of the object does not change direction, this is called **linear acceleration**.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] **Deceleration** or **retardation**, on the other hand, is the component of the acceleration in the opposite (or antiparallel) direction to the tangential velocity.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] **Radial acceleration** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motions) is the component of the acceleration that changes the direction of the object's velocity.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] In Newtonian mechanics, the acceleration of a mass arises from forces acting on it, with its *net* acceleration being a result of the *net* force acting on it.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] By Newton's second law, the magnitude of the *net* acceleration will be proportional to the magnitude of the *net* force acting on the object and inversely proportional to the mass of the object, while the direction of the *net* acceleration will be the same as the direction of the *net* force.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] An object's average acceleration ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}$ over a period of time is its change in velocity, $\Delta \mathbf {v}$ , divided by the duration of the period, $\Delta t$ .
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Mathematically, ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}={\frac {\Delta \mathbf {v} }{\Delta t}}.$ The average acceleration is the simplest way to measure acceleration, requiring only knowledge of the change in velocity and the change in time.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] In a strict sense, the average acceleration is the only *true* acceleration one is able to directly measure without appealing to an empirical law, meaning that it is the most fundamental form of acceleration measurement.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] The average acceleration is most often used to approximate the kinematics of an object by assuming that the velocity changes linearly with time.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Instantaneous acceleration is the limit of the average acceleration over an infinitesimal interval of time.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Acceleration has the dimensions of velocity (L/T) divided by time, i.e.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] The SI unit of acceleration is the metre per second squared (m s−2); or "metre per second per second", as the velocity in metres per second changes by the acceleration value, every second.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] An object moving in a circular motion—such as a satellite orbiting the Earth—is accelerating due to the change of direction of motion, although its speed may be constant.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] In this case it is said to be undergoing *centripetal* (directed towards the center) acceleration.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Proper acceleration, the acceleration of a body relative to a free-fall condition, is measured by an instrument called an accelerometer.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Newton's second law is normally applied in an inertial reference frame.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] In a reference frame accelerating with acceleration a (in one dimension), Newton's laws can still be used by introducing an inertial force (fictitious force) $F=-ma$ on a mass m , opposite the acceleration of the frame.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] This accounts for the tendency of the mass to maintain its inertial motion—to stay "as is," at rest or moving at constant velocity—while the frame accelerates.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] One example is that a person in an elevator feels heavier or lighter as the elevator accelerates or decelerates.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] If m is known, measurement of the supporting force on the mass can be used to infer the acceleration; this is the principle of a mechanical accelerometer.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] In general relativity, gravity and inertial acceleration may be locally indistinguishable (see General relativity).
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] As speeds approach the speed of light, relativistic effects become increasingly large.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] When a vehicle starts from a standstill (zero velocity, in an inertial frame of reference) and travels in a straight line at increasing speeds, it is accelerating in the direction of travel.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] If the vehicle turns, an acceleration occurs toward the new direction and changes its motion vector.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] The component of acceleration of the vehicle in the direction of its velocity is called a **linear acceleration** or **tangential acceleration**, its effect being the passengers on board experience as a fictitious force pushing them back into or away from their seats.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] When changing direction, the component of the acceleration perpendicular to the velocity is called **radial** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motion), the reaction to which the passengers experience as a centrifugal force (another fictitious force).
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] If the speed of the vehicle decreases, this is an acceleration in the opposite direction of the velocity vector, sometimes called **deceleration** or **retardation**, and passengers experience the reaction to deceleration as an inertial force pushing them forward.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Such deceleration is often achieved by retrorocket burning in spacecraft.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Both acceleration and deceleration are treated the same, as they are both changes in velocity.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Each of these accelerations (tangential, radial, deceleration) is felt by passengers until their relative (differential) velocity is neutralised in reference to the acceleration due to change in speed.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] where **u**n is the unit (inward) normal vector to the particle's trajectory (also called *the principal normal*), and **r** is its instantaneous radius of curvature based upon the osculating circle at time t.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Geometrical analysis of three-dimensional space curves, which explains tangent, (principal) normal and binormal, is described by the Frenet–Serret formulas.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] A frequently cited example of uniform acceleration is that of an object in free fall in a uniform gravitational field.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] The acceleration of a falling body in the absence of resistances to motion is dependent only on the gravitational field strength g (also called *acceleration due to gravity*).
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] In particular, the motion can be resolved into two orthogonal parts, one of constant velocity and the other according to the above equations.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] As Galileo showed, the net result is parabolic motion, which describes, e.g., the trajectory of a projectile in vacuum near the surface of Earth.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] , always points radially from the origin.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] , not parallel to the radial motion but offset by the angular and Coriolis accelerations, nor tangent to the path but offset by the centripetal and radial accelerations.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] plane in a point of an arbitrary curve in any higher dimension.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] In uniform circular motion, that is moving with constant *speed* along a circular path, a particle experiences an acceleration resulting from the change of the direction of the velocity vector, while its magnitude remains constant.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] The derivative of the location of a point on a curve with respect to time, i.e. its velocity, turns out to be always exactly tangential to the curve, respectively orthogonal to the radius in this point.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Since in uniform motion the velocity in the tangential direction does not change, the acceleration must be in radial direction, pointing to the center of the circle.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] This acceleration constantly changes the direction of the velocity to be tangent in the neighbouring point, thereby rotating the velocity vector along the circle.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] This acceleration and the mass of the particle determine the necessary centripetal force, directed *toward* the centre of the circle, as the net force acting on this particle to keep it in this uniform circular motion.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] The so-called 'centrifugal force', appearing to act outward on the body, is a so-called pseudo force experienced in the frame of reference of the body in circular motion, due to the body's linear momentum, a vector tangent to the circle of motion.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] The tangential component is given by the angular acceleration $\alpha$ , i.e., the rate of change $\alpha ={\dot {\omega }}$ of the angular speed $\omega$ times the radius r .
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] The sign of the tangential component of the acceleration is determined by the sign of the angular acceleration ( $\alpha$ ), and the tangent is always directed at right angles to the radius vector.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] In multi-dimensional Cartesian coordinate systems, acceleration is broken up into components that correspond with each dimensional axis of the coordinate system.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] The special theory of relativity describes the behaviour of objects travelling relative to other objects at speeds approaching that of light in vacuum.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Newtonian mechanics is exactly revealed to be an approximation to reality, valid to great accuracy at lower speeds.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] As the relevant speeds increase toward the speed of light, acceleration no longer follows classical equations.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] As speeds approach that of light, the acceleration produced by a given force decreases, becoming infinitesimally small as light speed is approached; an object with mass can approach this speed asymptotically, but never reach it.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Unless the state of motion of an object is known, it is impossible to distinguish whether an observed force is due to gravity or to acceleration—gravity and inertial acceleration have identical effects.
[src:alternating-current/acceleration] Albert Einstein called this the equivalence principle, and said that only observers who feel no force at all—including the force of gravity—are justified in concluding that they are not accelerating.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The Adams power plant followed an 1886 plan by engineer Thomas Evershed to tap the power of Niagara Falls, which involved a "hydraulic canal" and a 7,500 feet (2,300 m) brick-lined tunnel, when the Niagara Falls Power Company was formed.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The Cataract Construction Company, a new company formed to exploit the opportunity, led by president Edward Dean Adams, first formed the International Niagara Commission in 1890 to come up with a plan for harnessing the Falls.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The Commission favored electricity, but could not recommend a solution to Cataract.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] In 1892, George Forbes was hired as a technical consultant and in May 1893 he convinced the company to build a hydroelectric system based on polyphase alternating current.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] Westinghouse Electric was subcontracted to build 5,000 horsepower (3,700 kW) 25 Hz AC generators, based on the work of Nikola Tesla and Benjamin G.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] Morris Company of Philadelphia built the turbines based on the design of the Swiss company Faesch and Piccard.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The power plant went into operation on August 25, 1895.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The transformer house building was designed by the architectural firm of McKim, Mead, and White.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] Locally quarried limestone was used in its construction.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The transformer house was next to the power houses, which "built on the upper river, above deep excavations housing twenty-one generating units.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] Tailwater from the generators passed into a 7000-ft tailrace tunnel, which conveyed the water beneath the city to the lower river, near the present-day site of the Rainbow Bridge.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The 18-ft by 21-ft tunnel required over 3 years to build, used more than 16 million bricks in a four-course lining.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] 1, as it was then called, would eventually generate 50,000 horsepower (37 MW) of electricity.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] There were 10 generator rated 5,000 horsepower (3.7 MW) of the outside revolving field, vertical shaft type.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The generators were separated into two banks of five generators each with independent switchboards.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The output was at 2,000 volts to serve in and around Niagara Falls.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] There were transformers to step up the voltage to 10,000 volts to serve the medium distance around Niagara Falls areas.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The voltage was also stepped up to 20,000 to serve the longer distance for Buffalo, Lockport, and Tonawanda.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The station was the model for a second similar station built in 1904.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The entire plant was officially named after Edward Dean Adams in 1927.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The original Westinghouse generators remained in operation until the plant closed in 1961, having been replaced by the Robert Moses Niagara Power Plant and the Lewiston Pump-Generating Plant.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The Power Plant's main arch is found on Goat Island as the Power Portal.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] The building was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1975 and was designated a National Historic Landmark in 1983 and an IEEE Milestone in 1990.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] It is located off 15th St., just south of Buffalo Avenue.
[src:alternating-current/adams-power-plant] It is a major contributing feature to the Niagara Falls National Heritage Area.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:alternating-current/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] An **AC/DC receiver design** is a style of power supply of vacuum tube radio or television receivers that eliminated the bulky and expensive AC-only mains transformer.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Having no mains transformer, receivers could operate from a DC supply as well as an AC supply (i.e., "AC/DC"), a feature which became less important as DC domestic electricity fell out of use.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] The design was maintained regardless due to its lower cost.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] In the early days of radio, mains electricity was supplied at different voltages in different places, and either direct current (DC) or alternating current (AC) was supplied.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] There are three ways of powering electronic equipment.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] AC-only equipment would rely on a transformer to provide the voltages for heater and plate circuits.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] AC/DC equipment would connect all the tube heaters in series to match the supply voltage; a rectifier would convert AC to the direct current required for operation.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] When connected to a DC supply, the rectifier stage of the power supply performed no active function.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] DC-only equipment would only run from a DC supply and included no rectifier stage.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] DC is no longer (or extremely rarely) used for mains power distribution.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Different radio set models were required for AC, DC mains, and battery operation.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] For example, a 1933 Murphy radio with essentially the same circuit had different models for AC supply, DC supply, and battery operation.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] The introduction of AC/DC circuitry allowed a single model to be used on either AC or DC mains as a selling point, and some such models added "Universal" to their name (such sets usually had user-settable voltage tapping arrangements to cater for the wide range of voltages).
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] The first AC/DC design of radio was the All American Five.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] The sole aim of the design was to eliminate the mains transformer.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] The lower cost of transformerless designs remained popular with manufacturers long after DC power distribution had disappeared.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Several models were produced which dispensed with the power transformer, but had circuit features which only allowed operation from AC.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Some early models were available in both AC-only and AC/DC versions, with the AC/DC versions sometimes slightly more expensive.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Television receivers were first commercially sold in England in 1936 for the new 'Television Service' broadcast by the British Broadcasting Corporation.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] All pre World War II sets used mains transformers and consequently were AC only.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] In 1948 Pye released the first television receiver, the B18T, to employ the AC/DC design to eliminate the mains transformer when operated off 240 V mains.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Pye's marketing material did not mention the set's ability to operate from a DC supply, possibly because there were no DC supplies within the reception range of Alexandra Palace television station, then Britain's only operating transmitter.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Other manufacturers adopted the design; they, and later also Pye, sold them as AC/DC sets; the technique was used for many decades.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Later designs were able to operate from 220 Vac; as a typical example Philips sold the AC/DC Fapesa TV-9 in Argentina c.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] 1965, a country with nominal 220 Vac mains (often lower in practice).
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Vacuum tube equipment used a number of tubes, each with a heater requiring a certain amount of electrical power.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] In AC/DC equipment, the heaters of all the tubes are connected in series.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] All the tubes are rated at the same current (typically 100, 150, 300, or 450 mA) but at different voltages, according to their heating power requirements.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] If necessary, resistance (which can be a ballast tube (barretter), a power resistor or a resistive mains lead are added so that, when the mains voltage is applied across the chain, the specified heating current flows.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Some types of ballast resistors were built into an envelope like a tube that was easily replaceable.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] With mains voltages of around 220 V, the power dissipated by the additional resistance and the voltage drop across it could be quite high, and it was common to use a resistive power cable (mains cord) of defined resistance, running warm, rather than putting a hot resistor inside the case.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] If a resistive power cable was used, an inexperienced repairer might replace it with a standard cable, or use the wrong length, damaging the equipment and risking a fire.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] AC/DC equipment did not require a transformer, and was consequently cheaper, lighter, and smaller than comparable AC equipment.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] This type of equipment continued to be produced long after AC became the universal standard due to its cost advantage over AC-only, and was only discontinued when vacuum tubes were replaced by low-voltage solid-state electronics.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] A rectifier and a filter capacitor were connected directly to the mains.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] If the mains power was AC, the rectifier converted it to DC.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] If it was DC, the rectifier effectively acted as a conductor.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] When operating on DC, the voltage available was reduced by the voltage drop across the rectifier.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Because an AC waveform has a voltage peak that is higher than the average value produced by the rectifier, the same set operating on the same root mean square AC supply voltage would have a higher effective voltage after the rectifier stage.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Areas with 220–240 volt AC supplies could develop higher plate voltage with a simple rectifier.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Transformerless power supplies were feasible for television receivers in 220–240 volt areas.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Additionally, the use of a transformer allowed multiple independent power supplies from separate transformer windings for different stages.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] In an AC/DC design there was no transformer to isolate the equipment from the mains.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Much equipment was built on a metal chassis which was connected to one side of the mains.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Because no power transformer was used, "hot chassis" construction was required: one of the mains power lines became the negative side of the power supply, connected to the chassis, and all metal parts in metallic contact with it, as common "ground".
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] With AC power, the neutral, rather than live, line should be connected to the chassis; touching it, while highly undesirable, is usually relatively safe—the neutral conductor is normally at or near earth potential.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] But if used with a two-pin power plug (or an incorrectly wired three-pin one), any metal that the user could touch was an electrocution hazard, connected to mains live.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Consequently equipment was made with no metal connected to the chassis exposed even in predictable abnormal situations, such as when a plastic knob came off a metal shaft, or small fingers poked through ventilation holes.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Service personnel working on energized equipment had to use an isolation transformer for safety, or be mindful that the chassis could be live.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] AC-only vacuum tube equipment used a bulky, heavy, and expensive transformer, but the chassis was not connected to the supply conductors and could be earthed, making for safe operation.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Transformerless "hot chassis" televisions continued to be commonly manufactured long after transistorisation rendered live-chassis design obsolete in radios.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] By the 1990s, inclusion of audio-video input jacks required elimination of the floating ground as TVs needed to be interconnectable with VCRs, game consoles and video disc players.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] The widespread replacement of cathode ray tubes with liquid crystal displays after the turn of the millennium resulted in televisions using primarily low voltages, obtained from switching power supplies.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] The potentially-hazardous "floating chassis" was no more.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] In the past, 110–120 V was not high enough for higher-power tube audio and television applications, and only suitable to operate low-power radio and audio equipment such as radio receivers.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Higher-powered 110–120 V audio or television equipment needed higher voltages, which were obtained using a step-up transformer based power supply, or sometimes an AC voltage doubler, therefore operating off AC only.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Some AC/DC equipment was designed to be switchable to be able to operate off either 110 V AC (possibly with a voltage doubler) or 220–240 V AC or DC.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Television receivers were produced which could run off 240 V AC or DC.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] The voltage was not high enough to power some circuits, so energy was recovered during the flyback period from the primary of the line output transformer to provide a boosted HT (vacuum tube) (high tension) supply.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] In a typical vacuum tube colour TV set, the line output stage had to boost its own HT supply to between 900 and 1200 volts (depending on screen size and design).
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Transistor line output stages, although not requiring supply voltages above the rectified mains voltage, nevertheless still developed extra voltage over the normal supply rail to avoid complicating the power supply circuitry.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] A typical transistor stage would produce between 20 and 50 'extra' volts.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] Some details of the way in which the nominally 190 volts HT supply was boosted to nearly 500 volts in the 1951 Bush TV22 are described in a technical publication.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] AC/DC televisions were produced well into the color and semiconductor era (some sets were tube/semiconductor hybrids).
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] With widespread adoption of solid-state design in the 1970s, voltage and power requirements for tabletop portable radio receivers dropped significantly.
[src:alternating-current/dc-receiver-design] One common approach was to design a battery-powered radio (typically 6 volts DC from four dry cells) but include a small built-in step down transformer and rectifier to allow mains electricity (120 V or 240 V AC, depending on region) as an alternative to battery-powered operation.
